    pearls: ["The 'window of opportunity' for HT: initiate within 10 years of menopause onset or before age 60 — this timing minimizes cardiovascular risk and may confer cardioprotection","Transdermal estradiol does NOT increase VTE risk (unlike oral estrogen) because it bypasses hepatic first-pass metabolism and does not increase clotting factor production","Vaginal estrogen is NOT systemically absorbed at clinically significant levels — it does not require progestogen opposition and is safe in most breast cancer survivors per ACOG","The WHI study results apply to OLDER postmenopausal women (average age 63) initiated on HT — results should not be extrapolated to symptomatic younger women starting HT near menopause onset","Compounded bioidentical hormones are NOT recommended by NAMS, ACOG, or the Endocrine Society — FDA-approved bioidentical options (estradiol patch, micronized progesterone) provide standardized dosing with safety monitoring","Hot flashes are most common in the first 2 years after menopause but may persist for 7+ years in some women; symptom duration guides treatment planning"],
