    pearls: ["MEN1 = '3 Ps': Parathyroid (95%), Pancreatic NETs (40%), Pituitary adenomas (30%) — hyperparathyroidism is typically the FIRST and most common manifestation","MEN2A = Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (95%), Pheochromocytoma (50%), Primary Hyperparathyroidism (20-30%); MEN2B = MTC (100%), Pheochromocytoma (50%), Mucosal Neuromas, Marfanoid habitus — NO hyperparathyroidism","CRITICAL RULE: In MEN2, ALWAYS screen for and resect pheochromocytoma BEFORE thyroidectomy — undiagnosed pheochromocytoma during surgery can cause fatal hypertensive crisis from anesthetic manipulation","Prophylactic thyroidectomy timing is guided by SPECIFIC RET codon mutation: MEN2B (M918T) = within 6 months of life; highest risk MEN2A (C634) = by age 5 — genotype-phenotype correlation is strong","Serum calcitonin is the tumor marker for medullary thyroid carcinoma — use for screening in RET carriers and for postoperative surveillance of recurrence; CEA is a secondary marker","Genetic testing for MEN syndromes should be offered to ALL first-degree relatives beginning in early childhood (age 3-5 for MEN2A, infancy for MEN2B) — early detection enables prophylactic intervention before cancer develops"],
